✔ Correct way
Hit Yahoo 1 stock at a time, every 120ms.
Why 120ms?
500 stocks × 120ms = 60 seconds


This means:
- You fetch all 500 stocks in 1 minute
- You never burst
- You never get rate‑limited
- You never overload Yahoo

⭐ THE REAL BLUEPRINT (This is the final architecture)
🟩 1. Split 500 stocks into a queue
Queue<String> yahooQueue = new LinkedList<>(all500Symbols);


🟦 2. Scheduler runs every 120ms
@Scheduled(fixedRate = 120)
public void fetchNextStock() {
    String symbol = yahooQueue.poll();
    if (symbol != null) {
        fetchYahooPrice(symbol);
        yahooQueue.add(symbol); // put it back for next cycle
    }
}


This means:
- Every 120ms → fetch 1 stock
- In 60 seconds → fetch all 500
- Then repeat

⭐ WHAT WE FETCH FROM YAHOO
For each stock:
- previousClose
- lastPrice (anchorPrice)
We store it in memory:
symbolStateMap.put(symbol, state);



⭐ LIVE PRICE DOES NOT COME FROM YAHOO
Yahoo only gives:
- anchorPrice (once per minute)
- previousClose
TickEngine generates:
- tickPrice (every 1 second)
- volatility
- spread
This is your live price.

⭐ WHEN USER HITS /explore/top-gainers
We do NOT call Yahoo.
We do:
sort all 500 SymbolState by changePercent
take top 20–30
return


This is instant.

